<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-261-812  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 261 812.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  March 12 1990 v4 n10 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army proposes moratorium on all ADP procurements. (wants immediateand almost complete moratorium on administrative automated dataprocessing system purchases)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Poos, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Army Lt Gen Jerome B. Hilmes, Dir of Information Systems forcommand, control, communications and computers (C4), sent ateletype to Army commands stating that Army Headquarters isconsidering a moratorium on the acquisition of automated dataprocessing (ADP) equipment and development of software that do notdirectly affect the Army's combat capabilities.andP;  The moratorium isnecessary to offset a proposed $288.1 million reduction in the FY1991 Pentagon ADP budget.andP;  The Army's proposal is also prompted bythe Defense Department's Corporate Information Management (CIM)initiative, the goal of which is to standardize certain ADPsystems as unitary, agencywide systems which could save as much as$2.18 billion by the end of FY 1995.andP;  The two exemptions to theArmy proposal are cost-effective, high-benefit essential commandsystems and candidate systems for the CIM program.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ProposalExpendituresLimitationsData ProcessingDefense ContractsGoals and ObjectivesUnited States. Army.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>